<subSubSection id="23620C320F252356DECC29A166C24B08" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="156B0265293764AD2F2C1D23ABEF0B56" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">
<taxonomicName id="C416554D754C56DA6250EABFF1FA45ED" authorityName="Heyden" authorityYear="1870" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Tachypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curtus">Tachypus curtus</taxonomicName>
Heyden, 1870: 65. Type locality: &quot;Valenzia, Albufera [Spain]&quot; (original citation). Syntype(s) [2 originally cited] location unknown (possibly in DEI).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="233AF12A50459273D01D09C6784DD072" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="34D40FC4B7DE44D7CC6CA7BAB250F0C4" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ADFCDB03EE69B9D48657ACF38FD88CC0" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">
This European and North African subspecies is adventive in North America where it is known from Maine (Larochelle and 
<normalizedToken id="27D3155634638476EBDA79AF8768531E" originalValue="LariviÃ¨re">Lariviere</normalizedToken>
1990a: 28, 33, as 
<taxonomicName id="2CB200E0AF10DA7BE7743F905084DD3B" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1760" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="42ADF82465EC9753A079A1211FEFD615" italics="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Asaphidion flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and southeastern New Hampshire (Bell 1989b: 204, as 
<taxonomicName id="6B87C63D73193184687047348F9F12E0" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1760" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="16088F0276B376DD244DDE657FF71BA9" italics="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Asaphidion flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) to Long Island, New York (Davidson and Langworthy 1981: 280, as 
<taxonomicName id="59C08EA20EED54BDF2DEE3CAEED81881" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1760" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="40AC374B7FF9F2FE5972429A28A492F0" italics="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Asaphidion flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The first inventoried specimens collected on this continent were found in the late 1920s in Long Island (Cooper 1930: 21, as 
<taxonomicName id="6E2C4962ECABC92A74E0FA96B39EB52F" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1760" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="A5D3C03F800E9F74EC9E942E6F6AF786" italics="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Asaphidion flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the next ones were found in 1976 also on Long Island (Davidson and Langworthy 1981: 280).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C539B02C6C74434B346F1C8C81E408BB" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" type="records">
<paragraph id="4B17A089E38791E5A4EC83C281EE7833" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Records.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3238E4D1F62BB6C7986AC4C3AAB46B41" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">
<emphasis id="8ACBFFFDD541745272457F509B7BDBA1" bold="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">USA</emphasis>
: CT, MA, ME, NH, NY, RI - 
<emphasis id="3FE25E7A349A4D1AF942D410C3427FE3" bold="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Adventive</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DD84E9D4E2C9EEA7DB4C568584446A7A" lastPageId="346" lastPageNumber="347" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" type="note">
<paragraph id="2B1D4AD6282466FDF360B565D35C9C52" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E1FB4CDE49001DC22281AECB2D85F763" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">
Two other subspecies, one from Morocco (
<taxonomicName id="6163D26836A00F5E9B59F302081430F3" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="curtum" subSpecies="moroccanum">
<emphasis id="4BCEA475455E0B1014B068E31FC05306" italics="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Asaphidion curtum moroccanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Antoine) and the other from the Canary Islands (
<taxonomicName id="D7FA58262C4C3D9287CC184A9F1B2090" authorityName="Uyttenboogaart" authorityYear="1928" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="curtum" subSpecies="delatorrei">
<emphasis id="15FAFC0479E9A1135EAE86492885B737" italics="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Asaphidion curtum delatorrei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Uyttenboogaart), are recognized.
</paragraph>
<caption id="73110B62B7BD30A8BFAF633B9C3860E6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/30923" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" start="Figure 22" startId="F22">
<paragraph id="F3F340395BF02CF4ADC0F551586BC9E5" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">
<emphasis id="428999717549A6B1DECBC10A660F7CF5" bold="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">
<pageBreakToken id="EDA0DA4F9B1384491ACB3297560718ED" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" start="start">Figure</pageBreakToken>
22.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="F45C309DB156CCFAD6BE146C4A080885" authority="curtum" authorityName="curtum (Heyden" authorityYear="1870" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="curtum" subSpecies="curtum">
<emphasis id="F840AE06DB3D4C0ACC11AB1CA801F965" italics="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">Asaphidion curtum curtum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Heyden). This adventive bembidiine was reported in the North American literature under the name 
<taxonomicName id="FA4E343721071AF2719CAAAA22E933A5" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1760" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="C080E45A83F0090B7A50640DDCBE158E" italics="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">Asaphidion flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Linnaeus) until a study of the male genitalia showed that the specimens were in fact conspecific with the morphologically similar 
<taxonomicName id="A6F6F73DADE9173EB25724332C3EF921" baseAuthorityName="Heyden" baseAuthorityYear="1870" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curtum">
<emphasis id="93D7778D0A71546A0F298D6A27902883" italics="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">Asaphidion curtum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="46E6542B3AE2F83CD7EA4F545490A200" authorityName="des Gozis" authorityYear="1886" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="163873F2D26A1CB669C7EAF14355A77B" italics="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">Asaphidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are odd-looking bembidiines and Linnaeus originally associated them with tiger beetles probably because of their large eyes and absence of elytral striae.
</paragraph>
</caption>
